Human-readable synopsis: InfectiousDiseaseScenario is a data type defined in the Apollo Standard, which represents an ecosystem at simulator time zero that has at least one infection process affecting at least one population.
Creator: Michael Wagner, John Levander, Nicholas Millett, William Hogan

Human-readable synopsis: This specification describes a tabular format in which output from a disease transmission model is represented.
Creator: John Levander, Nicholas Millett

Human-readable synopsis: This specification describes a tabular format in which output from a disease transmission model is represented.
Creator: John Levander, Nicholas Millett

Human-readable synopsis: This specification describes a tabular format for reporting case count data.  The data are coded using standard systems, including ISO 8106 for representing time, SNOMED for identifying diseases, and Apollo XSD for identifying locations, case types, and case count types.
Creator: John Levander, Max Sibilla, Wilbert van Panhuis

Human-readable synopsis: This specification describes the PHYLIP format, a format used for most input and output files used by PHYLIP, the Phylogeny Inference Package.  PHYLIP is a package of programs for inferring phylogenies (evolutionary trees). It has been distributed since 1980, and has over 30,000 registered users, making it the most widely distributed package of phylogeny programs.
Creator: Joseph Felsenstein

Human-readable synopsis: This specification describes two tabular formats:  one for households and the other for persons.
Creator: Samuel Ventura, Lee Richardson, Shannon Gallagher, Bill Eddy

Human-readable synopsis: This specification describes two tabular formats:  one for households and the other for persons.
Creator: Samuel Ventura, Lee Richardson, Shannon Gallagher, Bill Eddy

Human-readable synopsis: This specification describes four tabular formats:  for representing households, persons, schools and workplaces.
Creator: Samuel Ventura, Lee Richardson, Shannon Gallagher, Bill Eddy

Human-readable synopsis: This specification describes a tabular format that describes a nationwide synthetic population of households and persons called the 2010 U.S. Synthesized Population dataset, which was developed by RTI International. The synthetic population is a detailed, spatially-explicit representation of the socio-demographic distribution of the U.S. population in a microdata form. The data are distributed in a compressed file containing a series of ASCII files with comma separated value.
Creator: William Wheaton

identifier (can be string or IRI): biosharing id will be available soon
Human-readable synopsis: Project Tycho 2.0 datasets include counts of cases for conditions (i.e. disorders) in countries reported by health agencies. These counts can be specified for different geographical regions within a country, for different time intervals, for various age ranges and/or subpopulations, and can represent fatalities (deaths) or not. Each datafile includes variables to specify the attributes of each count, as indicated below. Counts may not be available for all locations and time periods; missing information is indicated as "NA".
This specification describes four tabular formats named:  population-yucatan.txtlocations-yucatan.txtimmunity-yucatan.txtnetwork-yucatan.txt
Creator: Thomas Hladish, Carl Pearson, Dennis Chao

Human-readable synopsis: This specification describes two tabular formats for representing count data for a location at a point in time.  The formats differ in that one represents locations as points using latitude and longitude, and the other format represents locations as polygons using an ID from the Apollo Location Service.
Creator: Sahawut Wesaratchakit, Amin Tajgardoon, Terence Sperringer

Human-readable synopsis: GeoJSON is a format for encoding a variety of geographic data structures.
Creator: Howard Butler, Martin Daly, Allan Doyle, Sean Gillies, Stefan Hagen, Tim Schaub

Human-readable synopsis: This specification describes how to represent a tree using nested parentheses.
Creator: James Archie, William Day, Wayne Maddison, Christopher Meacham, James Rohlf, David Swofford, Joe Felsenstein

Human-readable synopsis: FASTA format is a text-based format for representing either nucleotide sequences or peptide sequences, in which nucleotides or amino acids are represented using single-letter codes. The format also allows for sequence names and comments to precede the sequences.
Creator: William Pearson

Human-readable synopsis: Epi-Data JSON is the output format for storing query results from calls to the EpiData
Creator: Roni Rosenfeld

Human-readable synopsis: Epidemic is a data type defined in the Apollo Standard, which represents a process whose beginning is demarcated by accelerating infection acquisition by one or more host species of a particular pathogen in a particular location and whose end is demarcated by the time when the rate of of infection acquisition becomes constant.
Creator: Michael Wagner, John Levander, Nicholas Millett, William Hogan

Human-readable synopsis: CaseSeries is a data type defined in the Apollo Standard, which represents an investigation that has, as part, a population survey with an objective to count all participants in some disease outcome or some exposure process.
Creator: Michael Wagner, John Levander, Nicholas Millett, William Hogan

Human-readable synopsis: NEXUS is a file format designed to contain systematic data for use by computer programs.  The format is widely used in bioinformatics. Several popular phylogenetic programs such as PAUP*, MrBayes, Mesquite, MacClade and SplitsTree use this format.

data-format name: ape coding scheme for DNA sequences
Human-readable synopsis: This specification describes the coding scheme used in ape since version 1.10 for DNA sequences. Its aim is to provide fast algorithms and efficient programs for comparing sequences, particularly to compute evolutionary distances.
This specification describes the tabular format used to import time series data into EpiVis.
This specification describes the tabular format used to submit forecasts to the FluSight influenza challenge.
